The majority of participants, 71% (107/150), believed hand washing (with water only) to be the most effective measure to protect oneself from respiratory infections, while the uses of alcoholic hand rubs (37%, 56/150) and facemasks (35%, 52/150) were considered to be less effective. Only beliefs about the effectiveness of facemasks and hand washing with water and soap were significantly associated with their actual use (p
 < 0.01) (Table 4
).
